In [21]:
def Hypothesis_testing(col1, col2):
    t, pval= ttest_ind(col1, col2)
    if pval<0.05:
        return("pval ->" + str(pval) + ' -  reject null hypothesis')
    else:
        return("pval ->" + str(pval) + ' - accept null hypothesis')
In [22]:
print("Education " + Hypothesis_testing(df_copy['Education'],df['Education'] ))

Education pval ->1.0 - accept null hypothesis

Out of all 3 models (Logistic Regression, K-neighbours Classifier and Naive Bayes Classifier) Logistic Regression model perfomed better. The attribute were weak so the accuracy was very low.

Logistice regression performed better because Logistic Regression makes a prediction for the probability using a direct functional form where as Naive Bayes figures out how the data was generated given the results and KNN supports non-linear and uses 'feature similarity' to predict the values of any new data points. Naive Bayes assumes that the features are conditionally independent.
